docs.abstract: The young pastor wasn’t sure his congregation would like what he had to say and had no idea where it would lead all of them. He found himself at a crossroads of God, Alabama and Donald Trump.
docs.snippet: The young pastor wasn’t sure his congregation would like what he had to say and had no idea where it would lead all of them. He found himself at a crossroads of God, Alabama and Donald Trump.
docs.lead_paragraph: WILLIAMS, Ala. — In early 2017, a pastor in the Alabama countryside named Chris Thomas prepared to give his Sunday sermon. President Trump had been inaugurated the week before, and the new administration was already making headlines with a travel ban that included refugees from Syria.

headline.main: The Walls of the Church Couldn’t Keep the Trump Era Out
headline.print_headline: Culture Wars Reach the Pews, and Empty Them

docs.abstract: Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms issued a series of executive orders after the shooting of Rayshard Brooks, which has stirred protests and pushed the city into a broader reckoning over policing.
docs.snippet: Mayor Keisha Lance Bottoms issued a series of executive orders after the shooting of Rayshard Brooks, which has stirred protests and pushed the city into a broader reckoning over policing.
docs.lead_paragraph: ATLANTA — In the wake of the death of a black motorist by a white Atlanta police officer, the city’s mayor announced on Monday a series of changes aimed at dramatically overhauling how the Police Department uses force.

headline.main: Atlanta Mayor Tightens Rules on When Police Can Use Force
headline.print_headline: Atlanta Mayor Revises How the Police Use Force

byline.original: By Richard Fausset and Rick Rojas

docs.abstract: I want this time to be different and there are moments when I think it might be.
docs.snippet: I want this time to be different and there are moments when I think it might be.
docs.lead_paragraph: Corporations finally believe black lives matter. Or they at least understand that they have to make it look like they believe black lives matter.

docs.abstract: For that to happen, some monuments — and the historical myths they supported — are going to have to come down.
docs.snippet: For that to happen, some monuments — and the historical myths they supported — are going to have to come down.
docs.lead_paragraph: It doesn’t necessarily follow that a nationwide protest over police brutality would, for some, become a reason to take action against Confederate statues and other controversial monuments. But it has. In just the last week, protesters have knocked down Confederate statues in Richmond, Va., Nashville and Montgomery, Ala., as well as monuments to Christopher Columbus in Boston and St. Paul, Minn.

headline.main: To Overturn Trump, We Need to Overturn White Supremacy
headline.print_headline: We Need to Overturn White Supremacy

docs.abstract: No question the Roosevelt sculpture has to go. But what of the Shaw Memorial in Boston? Eliminate or obscure it, or explain it?
docs.snippet: No question the Roosevelt sculpture has to go. But what of the Shaw Memorial in Boston? Eliminate or obscure it, or explain it?
docs.lead_paragraph: Some sights are so searing that you can’t unsee them. And, like it or not, you end up seeing the world through them. Reality hasn’t changed; you have, which makes you want to change reality. Right now.

headline.main: We Don’t Have to Like Them. We Just Need to Understand Them.
headline.print_headline: Seeing Monuments In a New Day’s Light

docs.abstract: The current civil unrest is deeply connected to the racial disparities exposed by the coronavirus crisis. “I’m just as likely to die from a cop as I am from Covid,” one organizer said.
docs.snippet: The current civil unrest is deeply connected to the racial disparities exposed by the coronavirus crisis. “I’m just as likely to die from a cop as I am from Covid,” one organizer said.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — When Mike Griffin, a black community organizer in Minneapolis, took to the streets in protest, he was grieving for two black men taken during the turmoil convulsing the country: George Floyd, who died after gasping for air under the knee of a white police officer, and his own godfather, who succumbed to Covid-19.

headline.main: ‘Pandemic Within a Pandemic’: Coronavirus and Police Brutality Roil Black Communities

docs.abstract: The president has employed the same kind of inflammatory language as George Wallace did in the 1968 campaign. Richard Nixon ran that year seeking the middle between the Alabama governor and Hubert Humphrey.
docs.snippet: The president has employed the same kind of inflammatory language as George Wallace did in the 1968 campaign. Richard Nixon ran that year seeking the middle between the Alabama governor and Hubert Humphrey.
docs.lead_paragraph: President Trump said last month that he had “learned a lot from Richard Nixon,” and many interpreted his hard-line response to the street protests of recent days as a homage of sorts to the 1968 campaign. The president’s Twitter feed has been filled with phrases famous from the Nixon lexicon like “LAW & ORDER” and even “SILENT MAJORITY.”

headline.main: Trump May Compare Himself to Nixon in 1968, but He Really Resembles Wallace
headline.print_headline: Trump Seeks to Shadow Nixon, but Echoes Wallace in 1968

docs.abstract: Democrats are decrying the problem of “systemic racism.” But to many, the policy solutions seem to leave the system intact.

docs.lead_paragraph: HOUSTON — Hundreds of American flags lined the street outside George Floyd’s funeral services, as if the deceased were a member of law enforcement, not a black man killed in its custody.

headline.main: For George Floyd’s Mourners, What Does ‘Justice’ Mean?
headline.print_headline: To Achieve Real Justice, Only a Drastic Overhaul Will Do, Some Say

docs.abstract: In an anemic rally and a video interview with his son, the president created awkward images and relived a battle with an incline.
docs.snippet: In an anemic rally and a video interview with his son, the president created awkward images and relived a battle with an incline.
docs.lead_paragraph: When he took the stage Saturday night in Tulsa, Okla., it had been more than three months since President Trump had held one of his treasured campaign rallies. But they say giving a rally speech is like walking down a gently inclined ramp: It’s incredibly treacherous and harrowing, but after what seems like an endless amount of time, you eventually reach bottom.

headline.main: Onscreen, the Trump Campaign Ramps Up, and Down
headline.print_headline: The Battle of the Ramp, From West Point to Tulsa
